{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"50534e0d-bf76-4d17-a5b9-84a81efd21a6","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\nAfter a .NET SDK update, your installed workloads (like `maui`) may lag behind the new SDK version. `dotnet workload update` pulls the latest workload manifests and packages that match your current SDK band, which is exactly what you need.\n\n**`dotnet workload repair`** is for fixing a corrupted installation (missing/damaged files) — it reinstalls the *same* versions, so it won't help if the workloads are simply out of date relative to the new SDK.\n\n**TL;DR:**\n- **Out of date** → `dotnet workload update`\n- **Corrupted install** → `dotnet workload repair`","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b8be6d13-0e42-4513-8ce4-f8caf3202795","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about whether to use `dotnet workload update` or `dotnet workload repair` to fix their .NET MAUI build issue after a SDK update. This is a general knowledge question that doesn't require exploring a codebase or running commands.\n\nLet me answer based on my knowledge of .NET workloads:\n\n- `dotnet workload update` - Updates all installed workloads to the latest available versions for the SDK band you're using. This is what you want when your workloads are out of date relative to the SDK.\n- `dotnet workload repair` - Reinstalls all installed workloads to fix a corrupted installation (e.g., missing files), but doesn't update them to newer versions.\n\n\nSince the user's workloads are out of date after the SDK update, `dotnet workload update` is the right command to use here.","outputTokens":371,"requestId":"A84D:2AD648:6514B4:74A14A:69FBE1C9"},"id":"44d19cf0-6d9e-4828-b518-6df20b84997c","timestamp":"2026-05-07T00:50:27.932Z","parentId":"040aee55-6801-405d-8343-b699da254b14"}
